hands_on_practices.solution:
We are asked to compute the commutator of two covariant derivatives acting on a smooth scalar field $\phi$. The covariant derivative of a scalar field equals its partial derivative:
$$

abla_{\mu}\phi=\partial_{\mu}\phi.
$$
Therefore,
$$

abla_{\mu}
abla_{
u}\phi=
abla_{\mu}(\partial_{
u}\phi).
$$
Since $\partial_{
u}\phi$ transforms as a covector, its covariant derivative is
$$

abla_{\mu}(\partial_{
u}\phi)=\partial_{\mu}\partial_{
u}\phi-\Gamma^{\lambda}_{\mu
u}\,\partial_{\lambda}\phi.
$$
Similarly,
$$

abla_{
u}
abla_{\mu}\phi=\partial_{
u}\partial_{\mu}\phi-\Gamma^{\lambda}_{
u\mu}\,\partial_{\lambda}\phi.
$$
The commutator is
$$
[
abla_{\mu},
abla_{
u}]\phi=
abla_{\mu}
abla_{
u}\phi-
abla_{
u}
abla_{\mu}\phi
=(\partial_{\mu}\partial_{
u}\phi-\Gamma^{\lambda}_{\mu
u}\partial_{\lambda}\phi)-(\partial_{
u}\partial_{\mu}\phi-\Gamma^{\lambda}_{
u\mu}\partial_{\lambda}\phi).
$$
Grouping terms gives
$$
[
abla_{\mu},
abla_{
u}]\phi=(\partial_{\mu}\partial_{
u}\phi-\partial_{
u}\partial_{\mu}\phi)-(\Gamma^{\lambda}_{\mu
u}-\Gamma^{\lambda}_{
u\mu})\partial_{\lambda}\phi.
$$
By equality of mixed partial derivatives for smooth scalar fields,
$$
\partial_{\mu}\partial_{
u}\phi=\partial_{
u}\partial_{\mu}\phi,
$$
and by the symmetry of the Christoffel symbols in their lower indices,
$$
\Gamma^{\lambda}_{\mu
u}=\Gamma^{\lambda}_{
u\mu}.
$$
Thus both terms vanish, yielding
$$
[
abla_{\mu},
abla_{
u}]\phi=0.
$$
